Which of the following statements is NOT correct regarding EnsDb.Hsapiens.v75, ensembldb, biomaRt, and EFO/ontologyIndex?

A. EnsDb.Hsapiens.v75 and ensembldb provide local, offline access to Ensembl gene models, including genes, transcripts, and exons.

B. biomaRt retrieves gene and annotation data by querying Ensembl (or other BioMart services) over the internet.

C. EFO/ontologyIndex are used to represent and traverse hierarchical phenotype and trait ontologies rather than gene annotation databases.

D. ensembldb and biomaRt both rely on ontology structures such as EFO to define gene–trait relationships.

Answer: D

Key reasoning
EnsDb.Hsapiens.v75
→ Local snapshot of Ensembl gene models (offline, versioned)
ensembldb
→ General framework behind EnsDb packages
biomaRt
→ Online query system for Ensembl/BioMart
ontologyIndex
→ Local ontology graph traversal (parents/children/ancestors)
Experimental Factor Ontology
→ Standardized phenotype/trait ontology used in GWAS and annotation
Key conceptual separation (high-yield)
1. Gene annotation layer
EnsDb.Hsapiens.v75 (snapshot)
ensembldb (framework)

👉 “What genes exist at this locus?”

2. Online annotation layer
biomaRt

👉 “Query Ensembl dynamically”

3. Ontology layer (phenotypes/traits)
EFO
ontologyIndex

👉 “How are traits/phenotypes structured and related?”

One-line memory trick
EnsDb / ensembldb = local genome
biomaRt = remote genome
EFO / ontologyIndex = phenotype ontology (not genes)
